&nbsp;
The cycle of meetings opens &nbsp;Tuesday 25 February &nbsp;at 18:30 &nbsp;at the Sala Fratel Vasco of the Istituto San Leone Magno con&nbsp;"Between social and artificial intelligence: what to do?",&nbsp;>a study with&nbsp;Antonio Palmieri,&nbsp;>founder and president of the &nerosp;Fondazione
&nbsp;
The second appointment, "Influencer: tra good practices e bad masters">,&nbsp; will be held &nbsp;Tuesday 25 March at 18:30&nbsp;presso il CTE Roma, inside the Tiburtina Station,&nbsp;with the patronage of the&nbsp;Fondazione Prioritalia. The meeting &nbsp; will see the participation of&nbsp;Sara Verrecchia,&nbsp;former of the project&nbsp;Social Warning of the Digital Ethical Movement, which will address the theme of digital influence and its impact on self perception, with a focus &nbsp; on food behavior disorders.
&nbsp;
The third and last appointment,&nbsp;Tuesday 15 April &nbsp; at 18:30,> will focus on the &nbsp;"Digital plates in schools"&nbsp; and will take place at&nbsp; the Auditorium of the University College Don Mazza. It will be an opportunity to deepen an increasingly widespread practice, which aims to empower schools and families in the use of digital tools > by children and adolescents. The meeting will host some school leaders, including Prof.&nbsp;Matteo Mennini,&nbsp; director of the San Leone Magno&nbsp; of Rome.
The meetings are based on a consolidated scientific assumption: the abuse of the &nbsp;smartphone and social media&nbsp;>can generate &nbsp; neurological and psychological consequences in younger people, &nbsp; digital dependence on anxiety and difficulty in managing expectation and frustration. The aim of the series of meetings is to provide &nbsp; tips and concrete solutions for a balanced approach.
“As an association we are convinced that devoting time to such a central theme for young people means reflecting on the type of society we are building” – states&nbsp; Antonio De Napoli,&nbsp; president of&nbsp; Civic Pass>.
“To take care of a conscious use of technology &nbsp;&nbsp;it means to take care of the quality of our society. We need kids on the net: I am not referring only to digital networks, as to the networks of people who want to participate as citizens active in change.” >
Antonio Palmieri&nbsp;- guest of the first meeting - says: “We are “small and poor” in front of digital platforms. Yet technology - at least for now - to work needs each of us. Our individual choices of use of digital tools > make the difference concretely.&nbsp; It is therefore a question of good use of our freedom and responsibility, but we must be aware that the power of us without power needs to be fueled by the most powerful gasoline there is: education. ”
The initiative is carried out in collaboration with the Solid Thought Foundation, the Digital Ethical Movement, the Association Per Roma> and the Sinderesi Foundation, &nbsp; engaged in educational and social projects inspired by ethics and civic responsibility.
